{
  "stem": "4284.3",
  "chunk_idx": 11,
  "model": "openai/gpt-oss-120b",
  "elapsed_s": 5.3,
  "sentences_input": [
    {
      "segment_idx": 18,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 12,
      "text": "It was only in the early '60s, maybe the late '50s, that I found out through historical research that in all the years till 1945, only two transports, a total of two, of juveniles ever left Birkenau for something that wasn't for extermination-- 165 before I went and 131 that I was in.",
      "word_count": 53
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 18,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 13,
      "text": "And the trucks that were used to transport from Birkenau to Auschwitz were exactly the same trucks that you could put the carbon monoxide exhaust into the van, into the truck, drive around for approximately a little bit longer to suffocate everybody, and then, bam.",
      "word_count": 45
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 18,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 14,
      "text": "So there were only 296 juveniles that ever actually, in an organized fashion, were selected and literally taken out for something other than extermination.",
      "word_count": 24
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 18,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 15,
      "text": "Of course, we didn't know that at the time.",
      "word_count": 9
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 18,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 16,
      "text": "I was in Auschwitz.",
      "word_count": 4
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 18,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 17,
      "text": "And my responsibility, with all 130 others, was to propagate horses, because Germany needed horsepower rather than motorized power for many of the functions in occupied countries and transportation.",
      "word_count": 29
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 18,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 18,
      "text": "And they wanted to have horses as quickly as possible.",
      "word_count": 10
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 19,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 0,
      "text": "So it turns out that of all the 131, there were only two of us who spoke German.",
      "word_count": 18
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 19,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 1,
      "text": "Consequently, even in the ghetto, being a [GERMAN], a German Jew, was not a very pleasant situation if the only language you speak is that of your enemy.",
      "word_count": 28
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 19,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 2,
      "text": "And so I learned Yiddish very quickly.",
      "word_count": 7
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 19,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 3,
      "text": "But I still, of course, even to this day, speak German.",
      "word_count": 11
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 19,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 4,
      "text": "So the question had come up that our responsibility was to take care of four horses each, cleaning the stable, and be responsible to mate them.",
      "word_count": 26
    }
  ],
